---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const post = postBySlug('gutter-cleaning-kilmarnock-ayr-autumn-2026-checklist')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Gutter cleaning',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'autumn gutter clean kilmarnock', 'gutter vacuum ayr', 'blocked gutters KA1', 'gutter checklist 2026'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [{ '@type': 'Place', name: 'Kilmarnock, Scotland' }, { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Ayr, Scotland' }],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        A short autumn gutter checklist for Kilmarnock, Ayr and the KA
        postcodes heading into winter 2026–27. What to look for the week
        after the first big leaf-drop, when to leave it alone, and the
        five signs that mean book this week, not next month.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <p>
        We still believe spring is the better window for a main clean —
        the long reasoning is in the
        <a href={`${BASE}/blog/gutter-cleaning-ayr-kilmarnock-spring/`}>Ayr
        and Kilmarnock spring post</a>. That said, autumn 2026 across the
        west of Scotland has been wet and windy, trees dropped early in
        Kilmarnock and Ayr, and plenty of folk need a quick
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/gutter-cleaning/`}>gutter clean</a>
        before the first proper storm of November lands.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a practical checklist — walk round the outside of your
        house, five minutes, and you will know whether to book or leave
        it. Full price bands and service details sit on the
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/guttering/`}>guttering service page</a>
        and in the
        <a href={`${BASE}/blog/gutter-cleaning-cost-kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock
        cost post</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>The 6-point autumn walk-around</h2>

      <h3>1. Look straight up at the eaves</h3>
      <p>
        Stand on the lawn, ten feet back from the wall. Look at the front
        edge of the gutter. If you see leaves hanging over the lip, a
        dark line of moss along the front, or seedling plants rooted in
        the run, you are overdue. That is not cosmetic — it is a dam.
        Next heavy rain, water overshoots the front edge and hits the
        render.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Check the downpipes in rain</h3>
      <p>
        On the next wet day, look at each downpipe. If water is running
        strongly through them, the gutters are flowing. If one downpipe
        is dry while the others run, or if water is overflowing from the
        hopper at the top, that run is blocked. That one needs clearing
        before the next storm.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Damp streaks on the wall</h3>
      <p>
        Dark streaks down the render directly under a joint or hopper
        mean the joint has been weeping quietly for weeks. Common on
        1960s and 1970s cast-iron hoppers in
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a> and the
        older Alloway and Prestwick housing in
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/ayr/`}>Ayr</a>. Left alone, the render
        cracks and water starts tracking behind it.
      </p>

      <h3>4. The inside of an upstairs corner</h3>
      <p>
        Go upstairs and check the corner of the ceiling in the bedroom
        nearest the eaves. A brown tide mark, soft plaster, or a musty
        smell says water is backing up at the gutter and soaking the
        wall top through the eaves. That is a whole-house problem if
        you leave it to February.
      </p>

      <h3>5. Moss carpet on the tiles near the gutter</h3>
      <p>
        A thick moss carpet on the slates nearest the gutter is not a
        gutter problem on its own. But on every rainfall it peels off
        in strings and ends up in the gutter. If you see a heavy moss
        mat at the eaves course, the gutter below is probably full.
      </p>

      <h3>6. Birds nesting in the hopper</h3>
      <p>
        Birds nesting in the hopper suggest the gutter is dry and full
        of the soft debris that builds a nest. That is a dead giveaway
        the gutter is blocked solid.
      </p>

      <h2>Autumn 2026 — how we quote</h2>
      <p>
        Same as the rest of the year — we do not hike prices because it is
        October. Every job priced individually against house size, access,
        condition and the length of the run. Typical jobs we cover in
        autumn across the KA postcodes:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Bungalow, single storey — KA1, KA2, KA3, KA7 or KA9.</li>
        <li>Standard 3-bed semi anywhere in Kilmarnock, Ayr, Troon or Prestwick.</li>
        <li>4-bed detached with garage run, complex back roofline.</li>
        <li>Kilmarnock town-centre tenements, Ayr seafront terraces, Maybole stone cottages with full-height cast-iron runs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Free no-obligation quote across KA1 to KA9, KA12
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/irvine/`}>Irvine</a>, KA17, KA18 and KA19.
        More on how we quote on the
        <a href={`${BASE}/pricing/`}>pricing page</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What the autumn clean actually looks like</h2>
      <p>
        Same kit as spring. No ladders on your lawn, no boot prints on
        the slates. A carbon-fibre vac pole with a camera on the end and
        a high-suction vac at the base. What is in the price every time:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>All gutters, hoppers and outlets vac-cleared.</li>
        <li>Downpipes flushed with water to confirm flow.</li>
        <li>Before-and-after photos of each run, sent by WhatsApp.</li>
        <li>All leaves, moss and silt bagged and taken away — we pay the tip fee.</li>
        <li>Bracket and joint check while the pole is up.</li>
        <li>Free written repair quote for anything we spot, no pressure.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Anything we flag feeds into our broader
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/roofing/`}>roofing and guttering repair</a>
        work — loose brackets, leaking joints, sagging runs, cracked
        fascia. You decide whether to book the fix; we will never add it
        to the invoice without asking.
      </p>

      <h2>When to leave it alone</h2>
      <p>
        If you cleaned in April, have no trees within five metres of the
        roof, no damp streaks, all downpipes running strongly on wet
        days, and no moss on the eaves course — you can safely skip
        autumn and do the next clean in April 2027.
      </p>
      <p>
        Two exceptions: mature trees near the eaves, and any property
        inside <a href={`${BASE}/areas/irvine/`}>Irvine</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/stewarton/`}>Stewarton</a> or
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmaurs/`}>Kilmaurs</a> with a hedge
        alongside the driveway. Both shed enough debris that one spring
        clean is not enough.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>

      <h3>When is the autumn window?</h3>
      <p>
        First weekend of November is our rule of thumb for the KA
        postcodes. Trees are mostly bare by then and you catch the
        debris before the first big low-pressure storm rolls in.
      </p>

      <h3>Can you clean after a storm has hit?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Post-storm leaf and twig clearance is a common same-week
        job. If a downpipe has split or a section of gutter has come
        loose, we can also make-safe and quote a repair from the same
        visit.
      </p>

      <h3>Do you do commercial properties?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Small commercial, retail units, light industrial. Scheduled
        maintenance contracts too — half the cost of one-off visits if
        you want spring and autumn booked in together.
      </p>

      <h3>How quickly can you get out?</h3>
      <p>
        We are booking roughly a week out through autumn 2026. If the
        issue is active — water pouring down a wall in a storm — we
        can usually get to you the same day across KA1, KA3 and KA7.
      </p>

      <h3>What if you find a bigger problem?</h3>
      <p>
        We photograph it, quote it separately, and you decide.
        The clean is still the clean. We do not bundle surprise repairs
        into the invoice.
      </p>

      <p>
        Five-minute walk round the garden this weekend, book the clean
        if you spot any of the six signs above. Cheaper now than after
        the first November gale.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />

  <CTABlock
    heading="Autumn gutter clean in Kilmarnock or Ayr?"
    sub="WhatsApp Fraser a photo of the house front and back — firm price back to you inside an hour."
    location="Kilmarnock & Ayr"
  />
</BaseLayout>
